239
00:14:08,067 --> 00:14:08,848
is the squint test.

240
00:14:10,079 --> 00:14:11,940
Here's a famous negative space image of a dog.

241
00:14:11,960 --> 00:14:14,340
If you have trouble seeing, squint,

242
00:14:14,560 --> 00:14:16,401
and the dog will probably come into focus.

243
00:14:20,382 --> 00:14:22,202
Squinting gives you the broad sense of a scene

244
00:14:22,622 --> 00:14:25,203
while minimizing the impact of the finer details.

245
00:14:25,683 --> 00:14:28,223
This is kind of like an auto gestalt simulator.

246
00:14:29,004 --> 00:14:30,704
Now to account for this, we actually

247
00:14:30,744 --> 00:14:33,025
implemented a squint tool in Unreal Engine 3.

248
00:14:34,234 --> 00:14:38,376
I don't know exactly who did it, I tried to figure it out and I couldn't, it got wild goose chase.

249
00:14:38,676 --> 00:14:42,919
But I had this image in my head of a programmer walking into a room full of artists

250
00:14:43,239 --> 00:14:46,201
and they're all squinting at their scenes and complaining of headaches.

251
00:14:47,342 --> 00:14:48,803
So essentially, with a click of this button,

252
00:14:49,163 --> 00:14:51,524
you could blur the frame buffer, making

253
00:14:51,564 --> 00:14:53,504
the scene in your editor viewport

254
00:14:53,884 --> 00:14:56,005
look just as it would as if you were squinting,

255
00:14:56,585 --> 00:14:58,046
but with less eye strain.

256
00:14:58,946 --> 00:15:00,127
And since I didn't have everything

257
00:15:00,167 --> 00:15:02,848
I wanted to show you today running in Unreal Engine 3,

258
00:15:03,468 --> 00:15:06,449
I tried to recreate that same squint effect using

259
00:15:06,529 --> 00:15:08,209
Photoshop's built-in blur filter.

260
00:15:09,090 --> 00:15:11,211
So here's face and favela side by side.

261
00:15:11,892 --> 00:15:14,814
And here they are with Photoshop's default blur filter

262
00:15:15,194 --> 00:15:17,656
to show you what each scene might look like if you were

263
00:15:17,756 --> 00:15:20,398
using that squint tool.

264
00:15:21,679 --> 00:15:24,021
Now if you can imagine yourself moving through these maps in

265
00:15:24,041 --> 00:15:27,403
real time, your eyes quickly scanning for enemies, these

266
00:15:27,523 --> 00:15:30,605
blurry images are similar to what your brain would process

267
00:15:30,806 --> 00:15:31,586
in a split second.

268
00:15:32,478 --> 00:15:38,040
And even without stopping to focus on any particular detail, you can see that face is

269
00:15:38,140 --> 00:15:39,760
still almost completely readable.

270
00:15:40,180 --> 00:15:42,920
The paths are there, the doors, the architecture, the shapes.

271
00:15:43,301 --> 00:15:47,621
It would be really simple for your brain to take this entire scene in quickly and make

272
00:15:47,701 --> 00:15:50,042
decisions quickly in game.

273
00:15:50,462 --> 00:15:54,703
Now, by contrast, favela has just become a jumble of bleeding colors.

274
00:15:55,203 --> 00:15:57,903
And the only real distinct feature there is the sky.

275
00:15:58,703 --> 00:16:01,264
Your brain has to struggle a little bit to interpret.

276
00:16:01,904 --> 00:16:03,405
the individual details.

277
00:16:03,765 --> 00:16:08,288
And even though that might happen in a split second, that's all it takes to affect your

278
00:16:08,308 --> 00:16:09,869
reaction time in combat.

279
00:16:10,149 --> 00:16:16,452
It slows down that decision-making process because you have to mentally focus and process

280
00:16:16,612 --> 00:16:20,655
each detail sequentially rather than taking in the scene as a whole.

281
00:16:21,695 --> 00:16:26,198
So squinting, shrinking, blurring, these are all really simple techniques that you can

282
00:16:26,298 --> 00:16:30,940
use almost at any time to ensure that your foreground and your background work together.

283
00:16:31,596 --> 00:16:35,120
The foreground and the background, if the foreground and the background are fighting for attention,

284
00:16:35,301 --> 00:16:36,482
then neither is going to win.

285
00:16:37,363 --> 00:16:39,005
Good use of negative space, however,

286
00:16:39,386 --> 00:16:44,252
can focus the player's attention on what you think are the important elements of your scene,

287
00:16:44,592 --> 00:16:47,636
meaning that you take an active part in the design process,

288
00:16:47,956 --> 00:16:50,880
that you can actually influence the experience of your players.

289
00:16:52,538 --> 00:16:58,125
Another way the brain works through a complicated scene is to break it down into what cognitive

290
00:16:58,145 --> 00:17:01,289
scientists call small, meaningful patterns.

291
00:17:02,130 --> 00:17:05,854
We take groups of objects that are similar and we quickly combine them into a single

292
00:17:05,974 --> 00:17:07,536
chunk that's easy to process.

293
00:17:08,537 --> 00:17:13,259
I wanted to visualize this process too, so leaning on Photoshop one more time, I used

294
00:17:13,299 --> 00:17:14,320
the palette knife filter.

295
00:17:14,960 --> 00:17:20,083
The palette knife processes an image, taking areas of similar color and combining them

296
00:17:20,223 --> 00:17:24,304
into one of the same color, just like our brains might do with visual information.

297
00:17:24,765 --> 00:17:29,327
So again, here's face and favela, and here they are processed with Photoshop's default

298
00:17:29,367 --> 00:17:31,508
settings on the palette knife filter.

299
00:17:32,582 --> 00:17:35,304
You can see that all the main features of FACE are still there.

300
00:17:35,725 --> 00:17:39,767
The paths, the doors, the assault points, everything comes through clearly, but by contrast,

301
00:17:40,388 --> 00:17:42,990
Favela becomes an obscure collection of blotches.

302
00:17:43,370 --> 00:17:47,093
You can't even distinguish the gameplay space from the architecture anymore.

303
00:17:48,814 --> 00:17:53,417
Now, this is significant because it says how we...

304
00:17:53,918 --> 00:17:54,018
we...

305
00:17:55,413 --> 00:18:01,394
affects perception in our maps. An image of well-defined borders is really easy for our brains to process.

306
00:18:01,914 --> 00:18:08,916
The first two circles here have nice clean borders, while the last circle is fuzzy, and it's more difficult to find the edges.

307
00:18:09,756 --> 00:18:16,438
When you look at an image, the main focal point is called the figure, and it's processed very quickly and easily

308
00:18:16,798 --> 00:18:22,139
when it's well differentiated from the background or negative space of the scene known as the ground.

309
00:18:23,075 --> 00:18:26,398
If your players can't discern a figure from ground,

310
00:18:26,718 --> 00:18:28,980
they'll have difficulty understanding how to navigate,

311
00:18:29,420 --> 00:18:31,282
and they'll struggle with target identification.

312
00:18:31,922 --> 00:18:34,264
And that's the basis for the classic image you see here,

313
00:18:34,684 --> 00:18:36,826
where ambiguity causes the brain to question

314
00:18:36,886 --> 00:18:39,528
whether it's looking at a candlestick or two faces.

315
00:18:41,009 --> 00:18:43,191
Each of you will make that decision very quickly,

316
00:18:43,231 --> 00:18:45,833
and somewhat ambiguously, because there is no right answer.

317
00:18:46,373 --> 00:18:47,854
In a split second, you'll decide

318
00:18:47,914 --> 00:18:50,216
whether you're looking at a candlestick or faces.

319
00:18:51,180 --> 00:18:54,722
But in a video game, that same split second can be an eternity.

320
00:18:55,602 --> 00:18:59,844
It can cost you life, it can throw an important play that ends the match.

321
00:19:00,265 --> 00:19:07,348
And the ambiguity of that decision means that your player isn't necessarily experiencing the design that you intended.

322
00:19:08,129 --> 00:19:11,991
Communicating clarity is a fundamental part of your role as a level designer.

323
00:19:12,851 --> 00:19:18,655
Now I've heard, I don't know for sure, but I have heard that Favela was the number one drop point in Call of Duty's campaign.

324
00:19:19,289 --> 00:19:22,770
and that their multiplayer version was actually one of their least popular maps.

325
00:19:23,570 --> 00:19:28,171
Now obviously, that feeling of overwhelming oppression and the frantic nature of combat

326
00:19:28,431 --> 00:19:32,672
was the whole point of that mission, but, and given the source material that they had

327
00:19:32,712 --> 00:19:37,453
to work with, they actually did a pretty fantastic job of distilling it down to a gameplay experience.

328
00:19:38,453 --> 00:19:43,014
I'm simply pointing out that there's a stark contrast that can be achieved if you focus

329
00:19:43,494 --> 00:19:46,755
on the use of negative space as a tool while you're designing.

330
00:19:47,707 --> 00:19:51,149
Nor am I claiming that I myself have been immune to these problems.

331
00:19:52,195 --> 00:19:55,116
We all struggle with it, and that's exactly why I wanted to talk about it today.

332
00:19:55,876 --> 00:20:00,277
In Gears of War, we had a map called Gridlock that was probably our most popular map in

333
00:20:00,297 --> 00:20:00,957
the franchise.

334
00:20:01,317 --> 00:20:05,198
And not surprisingly, the map has a pretty good use of negative space, with the shapes

335
00:20:05,238 --> 00:20:10,259
in the buildings contrasting with the different colors in the stone and against the background

336
00:20:10,279 --> 00:20:10,820
of the sky.

337
00:20:11,620 --> 00:20:15,421
Now, applying those same filters as before, the blur and the palette, you can see how

338
00:20:15,441 --> 00:20:18,901
the map's features still hold up.

339
00:20:19,762 --> 00:20:22,443
The cars are still distinct from the ground that they're sitting on.

340
00:20:22,483 --> 00:20:27,125
That gameplay space stands out from the buildings and there's a nice contrast against the background

341
00:20:27,165 --> 00:20:27,765
of the sky.

342
00:20:29,286 --> 00:20:34,188
Now, with Gears of War 2, we wanted to bring Gridlock back with an updated version that

343
00:20:34,448 --> 00:20:37,509
aged the environment to match the progression of the game's story.

344
00:20:38,269 --> 00:20:41,591
So we set out to do a theme that was overgrown.

345
00:20:42,231 --> 00:20:42,951
And in so doing...

346
00:20:43,896 --> 00:20:47,058
I think we actually lost a lot of that great contrast.

347
00:20:47,799 --> 00:20:52,222
So here's side by side of the same exact position in Gears 1 and Gears 2.

348
00:20:53,283 --> 00:20:59,588
And applying those same filters, you can see that even though Gears 2 has a high contrast sky to outline the shapes on the horizon,

349
00:21:00,148 --> 00:21:03,611
the overall sense of negative space is completely lost along the floor.

350
00:21:03,971 --> 00:21:05,993
There's no figure ground distinction.

351
00:21:06,493 --> 00:21:11,757
And important areas, like, hey, where the gameplay takes place, are just visually muddy.

352
00:21:13,803 --> 00:21:16,245
And while admittedly there are any number of other factors

353
00:21:16,565 --> 00:21:19,988
going on here, here's a chart that shows map popularity in

354
00:21:20,008 --> 00:21:22,791
Gears of War 2 as a factor of time played.

355
00:21:23,191 --> 00:21:25,713
And you'll notice that the new version of Gridlock is at the

356
00:21:25,753 --> 00:21:27,135
very bottom of the list.

357
00:21:29,460 --> 00:21:33,881
So, with Gears of War 3, we made this awesome decision to age the map even further.

358
00:21:34,341 --> 00:21:38,922
And this time the gameplay space became so overgrown that the gameplay completely fell apart.

359
00:21:39,642 --> 00:21:45,043
What was once the most popular map in the game became that one map that our testers hated playing.

360
00:21:45,803 --> 00:21:49,584
We hadn't changed the physical play space, the weapon loadout, or even the collision.

361
00:21:50,204 --> 00:21:52,625
But just that shift in tone and color...

362
00:21:53,225 --> 00:21:57,187
meant to a change in perception, a perception of negative space

363
00:21:57,467 --> 00:22:01,369
that took away the clarity that we had gotten from that original version of the map.

364
00:22:02,670 --> 00:22:05,692
So, we saw that this just wasn't working, and near the end of the project,

365
00:22:06,072 --> 00:22:07,132
we threw everything away.

366
00:22:07,553 --> 00:22:11,795
And we went back to a cleaner style that brought back the contrast we were aiming for,

367
00:22:12,135 --> 00:22:15,157
and highlighted the negative space aspects of the map.

368
00:22:15,917 --> 00:22:18,278
Not to belabor the point, but here's a screenshot of the map.

369
00:22:19,097 --> 00:22:23,148
blur and again with the other filter, the cars stand out from the ground, the gameplay

370
00:22:23,188 --> 00:22:27,098
spaces differentiated from the buildings, the whole scene has a nice contrast against

371
00:22:27,118 --> 00:22:27,640
the background.

372
00:22:29,254 --> 00:22:32,016
Sure enough, here's a chart showing this version of Gridlock

373
00:22:32,476 --> 00:22:37,158
back in the top three most played maps of Gears of War 3's lifetime.

374
00:22:37,979 --> 00:22:40,540
Application of negative space design techniques

375
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:42,961
led to an increase in map readability,

376
00:22:43,342 --> 00:22:47,044
and by extension, playability and enjoyability.

377
00:22:47,744 --> 00:22:49,545
So even though it was difficult to do at the time,

378
00:22:49,585 --> 00:22:52,967
I'm really glad that we made that call to throw everything away and change the map.

379
00:22:53,407 --> 00:22:55,728
And that chart tells me that the payoff was worth the effort.

380
00:22:56,276 --> 00:23:00,719
And we might not have actually been brave enough to do that had we not already struggled

381
00:23:00,759 --> 00:23:02,360
with this problem in another map.

382
00:23:02,861 --> 00:23:05,723
And ironically, that map was CTF Face.

383
00:23:07,444 --> 00:23:12,627
With the sequel to UT and Unreal Tournament 2003, we transitioned to a new version of

384
00:23:12,667 --> 00:23:17,071
the Unreal Engine, and we decided to update Facing Worlds along with it and take advantage

385
00:23:17,111 --> 00:23:18,471
of our new Egyptian setting.

386
00:23:19,613 --> 00:23:22,035
Now the Egyptian concept for zero is the nefer.

387
00:23:22,216 --> 00:23:26,099
It's a hieroglyph which roughly translates to the beginning of everything.

388
00:23:26,759 --> 00:23:28,941
It's a visual representation of the heart.

389
00:23:29,882 --> 00:23:34,645
Now to the ancient Egyptians then, you could say that the zero, or nothing, is the heart

390
00:23:34,865 --> 00:23:35,446
of everything.

391
00:23:36,126 --> 00:23:40,890
Now mark it as no coincidence that this same hieroglyph is also used to mean beautiful.

392
00:23:41,691 --> 00:23:45,434
Design is about beauty and simplicity and the importance of nothing.

393
00:23:46,285 --> 00:23:51,589
Sadly, I don't think any of that actually translated into UT2003's version of Facing Worlds.

394
00:23:52,389 --> 00:23:55,531
If you look at side-by-side comparisons of the two versions of the map,

395
00:23:55,591 --> 00:23:57,572
you can definitely see the similarities in the shape.

396
00:23:58,213 --> 00:24:00,514
But there are big differences in clarity.

397
00:24:01,315 --> 00:24:05,838
The original Facing Worlds map had 540 actors in the entirety of the map.

398
00:24:06,618 --> 00:24:07,679
The new version had over 4,000.

399
00:24:09,398 --> 00:24:13,280
The original Facing Worlds had 130 polygons in view from the sniping towers.

400
00:24:13,940 --> 00:24:19,143
This new Egyptian version had over 60,000 triangles in view from that same position.

401
00:24:19,544 --> 00:24:22,405
It's a 280 times increase in detail,

402
00:24:22,806 --> 00:24:27,128
which is quite significant, even broken down into meaningful patterns.

403
00:24:28,289 --> 00:24:29,489
So whenever you're building something,

404
00:24:29,970 --> 00:24:34,192
it's important to note how your layout will affect the player's gameplay experience.

405
00:24:34,994 --> 00:24:39,696
You may have heard of the principle of least effort, which tells us to minimize cognitive

406
00:24:39,756 --> 00:24:40,076
load.

407
00:24:40,637 --> 00:24:44,759
If you overwhelm your players with too much information, they're likely to struggle with

408
00:24:44,819 --> 00:24:45,459
processing it.

409
00:24:46,205 --> 00:24:48,507
And note that I'm talking about layout here.

410
00:24:48,967 --> 00:24:52,949
I'm not saying that the original Facing Worlds was a better map because it had less detail.

411
00:24:53,330 --> 00:24:58,073
You can and absolutely should add more detail to your maps as technology goes on, and I'll

412
00:24:58,093 --> 00:24:59,133
speak more on that in a bit.

413
00:24:59,513 --> 00:25:04,556
But in this particular instance, I'm specifically referencing the way that those details were

414
00:25:04,637 --> 00:25:05,157
implemented.

415
00:25:05,817 --> 00:25:07,639
the pyramid blocked lines of sight.

416
00:25:08,159 --> 00:25:10,581
The trees pulled our eyes away from the gameplay space,

417
00:25:10,641 --> 00:25:13,503
and the rolling terrain was dotted with these pools of water

418
00:25:13,563 --> 00:25:15,004
that got in the way of navigation,

419
00:25:15,064 --> 00:25:16,946
both visually as well as physically.

420
00:25:17,867 --> 00:25:21,209
Decorative pieces were used to separate combat areas,

421
00:25:21,590 --> 00:25:24,792
and it transferred these open spaces

422
00:25:25,172 --> 00:25:27,674
into really small combat closets.

423
00:25:28,558 --> 00:25:31,019
And because of the way our brains process visual information,

424
00:25:31,499 --> 00:25:33,640
all of these separate elements actually combine

425
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:36,480
to break up the level in undesirable ways.

426
00:25:37,761 --> 00:25:41,022
At Epic, we often talk about removing clutter from our maps.

427
00:25:41,402 --> 00:25:42,662
And what we're really trying to say

428
00:25:42,942 --> 00:25:44,883
is that we need a better use of negative space.

429
00:25:45,783 --> 00:25:47,823
Ask, where are your players' eyes going?

430
00:25:48,615 --> 00:25:53,762
Not always, but generally speaking, you want their eyes focused on the gameplay rather

431
00:25:53,782 --> 00:25:54,684
than the architecture.

432
00:25:55,505 --> 00:25:59,710
So rather than adding detail to an area to make it more beautiful, ask what you can remove.

433
00:26:00,331 --> 00:26:03,135
Is the extra geometry actually visually distracting?

434
00:26:03,815 --> 00:26:06,837
Are those new pools of water impeding navigation?

435
00:26:07,097 --> 00:26:12,639
Can you remove lights or highlight key areas with a sfumato-like effect?

436
00:26:13,140 --> 00:26:18,822
Maybe you can replace additional detail with just a simple shift in light or color.

437
00:26:19,903 --> 00:26:23,724
As a level designer, your goal should be to simplify and clarify.

438
00:26:24,125 --> 00:26:29,507
Streamline the experience and distill it down to those core important elements of gameplay.

439
00:26:30,658 --> 00:26:32,600
And remember my favela example from earlier.

440
00:26:33,160 --> 00:26:35,482
Geometric color, excessive polygons,

441
00:26:35,902 --> 00:26:38,404
can be just as troublesome as visual clutter,

442
00:26:38,884 --> 00:26:40,685
distracting shapes and rainbow colors.

443
00:26:41,266 --> 00:26:43,688
These two images each have a color histogram

444
00:26:43,728 --> 00:26:44,628
in the top right corner.

445
00:26:45,249 --> 00:26:47,110
And in the original face, you can

446
00:26:47,170 --> 00:26:49,071
see that color is distributed all

447
00:26:49,111 --> 00:26:52,254
across the histogram in high, mid, and low range values.

448
00:26:52,954 --> 00:26:56,456
And note that there's a single color spike on the low end.

449
00:26:57,594 --> 00:27:04,280
And that's indicative of one area filled with a large... of one color, which is the dark skybox.

450
00:27:04,680 --> 00:27:08,884
And that's important, because it means there's a large area filled by a single color

451
00:27:09,124 --> 00:27:12,246
that's going to give you good figure-ground contrast.

452
00:27:13,197 --> 00:27:18,600
Now by comparison, look at the UT2003 version, and there's just a massive bulge along the

453
00:27:18,660 --> 00:27:22,562
center of the histogram with no representation in the higher low ranges.

454
00:27:23,022 --> 00:27:28,204
And this indicates high midtone values, meaning that the color is going to be fairly uniform

455
00:27:28,425 --> 00:27:29,285
across the board.

456
00:27:29,665 --> 00:27:32,567
You're not going to get any great visual contrast.

457
00:27:33,007 --> 00:27:38,509
And we need that contrast because when objects look similar, our brains will process them

458
00:27:38,750 --> 00:27:40,290
as a single related group.

459
00:27:41,817 --> 00:27:46,138
And you can simulate that contrast by actually compressing the color and the histograms.

460
00:27:46,819 --> 00:27:52,240
And if you do that, the Egyptian version becomes, not surprisingly, this flat white sheet.

461
00:27:52,800 --> 00:27:56,942
While the original Facing Worlds becomes this really great example of figure-ground reversal,

462
00:27:57,342 --> 00:28:01,683
with all the negative spaces of the gameplay areas clearly delineated from the rest of the map.

463
00:28:02,223 --> 00:28:05,604
And I'm being generous here by including the moon in the background.

464
00:28:06,004 --> 00:28:10,806
That moon actually rotates out of view naturally as the skybox moves during gameplay.

465
00:28:11,326 --> 00:28:13,227
And if you remove that moon from the image,

466
00:28:13,547 --> 00:28:17,609
you get this perfect negative space outline of the level geometry.

467
00:28:18,309 --> 00:28:22,510
The clarity in this view is something that you would never get in that Egyptian version,

468
00:28:22,831 --> 00:28:27,792
where everything is just a wash of sameness that causes our brains to spend that extra time

469
00:28:28,133 --> 00:28:31,434
processing everything sequentially, detail by detail.

470
00:28:32,054 --> 00:28:36,537
And a simple chick as easy as squinting could have identified this problem quickly.

471
00:28:36,557 --> 00:28:42,000
Now that pyramid contributes to the problems because of its color similar to the rocks

472
