00:34:11,001 --> 00:34:12,642
But you can certainly see the impact

562
00:34:12,702 --> 00:34:15,763
that a complicated navigation network would have on AI.

563
00:34:16,915 --> 00:34:21,959
And the point that I'm trying to get across is that an AI network serves as an indicator

564
00:34:22,159 --> 00:34:24,001
of potential player behaviors.

565
00:34:24,761 --> 00:34:30,206
Clearly, a player trying to cross the same map has more choices to make, more obstacles,

566
00:34:30,566 --> 00:34:33,769
and more potential points for contention or confusion.

567
00:34:34,517 --> 00:34:40,422
the open negative spaces of the gameplay area have been broken up into these smaller collections

568
00:34:41,303 --> 00:34:47,248
of small areas. And just as our brain can get overloaded with visual information, it

569
00:34:47,388 --> 00:34:52,272
also gets bogged down while attempting to evaluate the differences between too many

570
00:34:52,432 --> 00:34:57,156
similar choices. Now, obviously we want to give our players

571
00:34:57,256 --> 00:34:58,076
interesting choices.

572
00:34:59,061 --> 00:35:01,062
and encourage emerging gameplay.

573
00:35:01,623 --> 00:35:03,964
But simply adding more isn't better.

574
00:35:04,664 --> 00:35:09,608
Gestalt research tells us that too much choice can actually lead to sensory overload.

575
00:35:09,848 --> 00:35:15,671
And this is a hot-button issue in autism research, where the belief is currently that autistic

576
00:35:15,731 --> 00:35:18,113
patients are unable to filter stimuli.

577
00:35:18,153 --> 00:35:23,456
They take in every detail of the world, every little bit, all around them, all the time.

578
00:35:23,956 --> 00:35:26,698
And the constant flow of information overwhelms them.

579
00:35:27,519 --> 00:35:29,440
What does this have to do with face and level design?

580
00:35:29,760 --> 00:35:35,984
Well, because our brains naturally combine details and establish patterns, more information

581
00:35:36,264 --> 00:35:40,206
means more detail that's potentially lost when things get combined.

582
00:35:41,067 --> 00:35:45,689
And the results from this perception study describe how much information was lost at

583
00:35:45,749 --> 00:35:47,330
different levels of visual threshold.

584
00:35:48,799 --> 00:35:53,462
Now it's important my point, the slide itself is visually overwhelming and difficult to

585
00:35:53,522 --> 00:35:58,825
read, but the quick takeaway here is that as you increase visual information, your brain

586
00:35:58,885 --> 00:36:04,289
will actually comprehend less, despite taking longer trying to process it.

587
00:36:05,069 --> 00:36:09,912
This is why balance and simplicity and flow are the founding principles of design.

588
00:36:11,173 --> 00:36:13,795
So back to Facing Worlds Classic and UT2004.

