00:43:24,964 --> 00:43:36,696
With blur in place, you can see how the extra geometry of the UT3 map still provides a readable contrast of playable versus non-playable space, meaning less information is lost.

710
00:43:37,496 --> 00:43:49,368
If we use the palette filter, you can see how important pieces of gameplay still stand out, with the sniper perches, the central paths, and the tower entrances nicely visible, just as in the original version of the map.

711
00:43:50,240 --> 00:43:53,683
Histogram values show a nice distribution in the RGB curves,

712
00:43:54,123 --> 00:43:55,825
aligned with spikes on either end,

713
00:43:56,165 --> 00:43:57,406
just like the original version.

714
00:43:57,827 --> 00:44:00,629
And compressing the histogram highlights

715
00:44:00,769 --> 00:44:04,693
good front ground delineation we need for the negative space

716
00:44:04,893 --> 00:44:08,376
areas of gameplay to be immediately readable by players,

717
00:44:08,857 --> 00:44:10,418
just as in the original version.

718
00:44:12,252 --> 00:44:16,035
If you highlight the path network, you can see the simplicity in the system that highlights

719
00:44:16,096 --> 00:44:22,821
the clarity of routes and options, only 144 nav points, 5 branches between tower and center

720
00:44:22,861 --> 00:44:23,242
of map.

721
00:44:24,042 --> 00:44:29,968
And we even went so far as to recreate the original, kind of soothing drum and bass music

722
00:44:30,008 --> 00:44:36,073
of the original face, removing all those distracting guitars and highlighting the negative aural

723
00:44:36,173 --> 00:44:36,473
space.

724
00:44:37,912 --> 00:44:41,514
Now, while I don't have any nicely defined metrics to show map popularity,

725
00:44:41,614 --> 00:44:43,035
sadly we didn't have them at the time,

726
00:44:43,416 --> 00:44:46,998
I can generate some anecdotal evidence to show that this map was a success.

727
00:44:47,679 --> 00:44:50,641
It was well accepted with several servers popping up

728
00:44:50,701 --> 00:44:54,144
that just ran this map 24 hours a day over and over,

729
00:44:54,584 --> 00:45:00,008
and even six years later, it's not uncommon to see those face-only servers still in heavy rotation.

730
00:45:00,939 --> 00:45:05,843
I can't find a single negative thread in the game's official forums, and if you're at all

731
00:45:05,903 --> 00:45:08,486
familiar with forums, that in itself is a complete miracle.

732
00:45:09,887 --> 00:45:15,192
In fact, I actually see a bunch of messages like these, praising it as the best version

733
00:45:15,412 --> 00:45:15,573
ever.

734
00:45:17,254 --> 00:45:23,318
So, UT3's version had a clear, front-ground delineation that made gameplay spaces defined

735
00:45:23,758 --> 00:45:24,218
and readable.

736
00:45:24,658 --> 00:45:29,762
High levels of detail were well-organized instead of distracting, and the balance of

737
00:45:29,842 --> 00:45:34,145
light, color, and shape left the map understandable even in the heat of combat.

738
00:45:34,605 --> 00:45:40,429
The oral and visual aspects of UT3's Facing Worlds embraced all the concepts of negative

739
00:45:40,469 --> 00:45:41,149
space design.

740
00:45:42,077 --> 00:45:48,299
As a designer, your job is to focus on subtracting the obvious and only adding the meaningful.

741
00:45:49,159 --> 00:45:54,641
I could never say definitively which version of Face was the best, but I feel very confident

742
00:45:54,661 --> 00:45:59,102
in saying that with the UT3 version, we were finally able to bring the essence of that

743
00:45:59,142 --> 00:46:04,204
original map forward in a meaningful way, and that we had the forethought to capture

744
00:46:04,244 --> 00:46:08,725
those aspects of negative space design that helped make the original map such a success.

745
00:46:09,845 --> 00:46:13,789
As an industry, we're often just kind of stumbling ahead.

746
00:46:13,889 --> 00:46:17,392
And there's this arms race to continually improve graphics

747
00:46:17,452 --> 00:46:18,793
and raise visual fidelity.

748
00:46:19,153 --> 00:46:22,536
And all too often, this simply means we're adding more stuff

749
00:46:22,616 --> 00:46:23,297
to our games.

750
00:46:24,258 --> 00:46:29,002
Open vistas have suddenly given way to these dense forests

751
00:46:29,102 --> 00:46:30,123
filled with foliage.

752
00:46:30,763 --> 00:46:32,765
Clear pathways have been replaced

753
00:46:32,785 --> 00:46:35,207
with these kind of techno-paneled and pipe-filled

754
00:46:35,267 --> 00:46:35,767
corridors.

755
00:46:36,727 --> 00:46:43,153
every bolt and every blade of grass rendered in startling detail. But do those details

756
00:46:43,334 --> 00:46:48,679
actually add to the gameplay experience? Or can they actually be detracting from the quality

757
00:46:48,779 --> 00:46:50,160
and enjoyability of our games?

758
00:46:51,140 --> 00:46:53,943
We didn't intend for the new versions of Face to be less popular.

759
00:46:53,963 --> 00:46:56,025
We didn't just randomly throw a map together.

760
00:46:56,626 --> 00:46:59,609
But we didn't think specifically about negative space.

761
00:47:00,250 --> 00:47:03,273
We didn't account for the way that the brain takes in information.

762
00:47:03,894 --> 00:47:09,520
We didn't distill our presentation to look at contrast or analyze the complexity of information

763
00:47:09,700 --> 00:47:10,401
being presented.

764
00:47:11,402 --> 00:47:14,685
Good design is about removing, not adding.

765
00:47:15,345 --> 00:47:17,607
And negative space is a very valuable tool

766
00:47:17,667 --> 00:47:18,608
in our design arsenal,

767
00:47:18,928 --> 00:47:20,529
certainly one that we tend to overlook.

768
00:47:21,269 --> 00:47:22,410
So, in the future,

769
00:47:22,911 --> 00:47:25,212
don't forget to look at what's not there.

770
00:47:25,753 --> 00:47:28,575
It can be so much more important than what actually is.

771
00:47:29,936 --> 00:47:30,176
Thank you.

772
00:47:41,262 --> 00:47:44,402
Looks like we have about 10 minutes if anybody has questions.

773
00:47:44,422 --> 00:47:46,363
I don't know if anybody does.

774
00:47:46,383 --> 00:47:47,603
I just want to run off.

775
00:47:49,503 --> 00:47:50,443
Can I start?

776
00:47:50,583 --> 00:47:50,824
Hello.

777
00:47:50,884 --> 00:47:52,704
Hey, go ahead.

778
00:47:52,764 --> 00:47:53,424
Hey, it's on.

779
00:47:53,444 --> 00:47:54,704
I 1,000% agree with everything you said.

780
00:47:55,504 --> 00:47:57,945
Where I work, our bread and butter is multiplayer maps.

781
00:47:58,505 --> 00:48:00,826
There's, I think, two additional points that could be made.

782
00:48:01,186 --> 00:48:04,366
One is keeping simplicity means that the callouts

783
00:48:04,406 --> 00:48:05,326
are that much more important.

784
00:48:06,134 --> 00:48:09,556
If you have detail everywhere, then you just don't know what to call out in the heat of

785
00:48:09,576 --> 00:48:09,836
battle.

786
00:48:09,876 --> 00:48:10,536
Where are you?

787
00:48:10,676 --> 00:48:12,757
I'm in the blue room, I'm in the red room, I'm in whatever.

788
00:48:13,097 --> 00:48:14,658
And the other one is effects.

789
00:48:15,118 --> 00:48:18,379
That's one of my pet peeves sometimes is when you have effects of papers blowing on the

790
00:48:18,440 --> 00:48:20,240
ground or sand going across the ground.

791
00:48:20,260 --> 00:48:24,122
In that split second, is it an enemy, is it a threat, or is it just pretty?

792
00:48:24,462 --> 00:48:29,264
That was a huge problem with that original Egyptian version of Face.

793
00:48:30,618 --> 00:48:32,439
there was these pools of water on the ground that you would

794
00:48:32,459 --> 00:48:34,620
stumble in and then it would splash and you couldn't get out

795
00:48:34,660 --> 00:48:38,283
and you're trying to swim and, you know, dust blowing and

796
00:48:38,363 --> 00:48:41,284
obscuring the grass. Yeah, it just absolutely could be a big

797
00:48:41,324 --> 00:48:41,585
mess.

798
00:48:41,625 --> 00:48:44,586
I totally agree. And I am an artist, by the way. So I still

799
00:48:44,606 --> 00:48:46,267
agree. 100% about it.

800
00:48:46,668 --> 00:48:47,348
Awesome. Thank you.

801
00:48:47,368 --> 00:48:49,609
Hi.

802
00:48:49,990 --> 00:48:50,510
Hi.

803
00:48:51,090 --> 00:48:57,114
I also spent a lot of time as an artist. And my question is,

804
00:48:57,814 --> 00:49:00,236
have you spent any time figuring out

805
00:49:01,457 --> 00:49:06,859
how to create a rule set for this that could be applied to procedural generation of levels?

806
00:49:07,299 --> 00:49:10,381
That is an area that we're just starting to get into at Epic.

807
00:49:11,361 --> 00:49:15,723
We are kind of transitioning away from traditional level design in terms of

808
00:49:16,443 --> 00:49:20,225
building blocks and pieces and leading more into procedural stuff.

809
00:49:20,645 --> 00:49:22,366
Sadly, I can't really talk about that yet.

810
00:49:23,427 --> 00:49:26,468
But I can say that in the past we...

811
00:49:27,651 --> 00:49:29,992
This isn't, it's not like we walked around the office saying,

812
00:49:30,052 --> 00:49:32,014
you need better negative design in your maps.

813
00:49:32,374 --> 00:49:34,395
But we do actually use those terms.

814
00:49:34,435 --> 00:49:37,237
We do talk about the way that shapes are organized.

815
00:49:37,297 --> 00:49:40,198
We do talk about contrast and balance and all those things.

816
00:49:41,059 --> 00:49:43,661
And like I said, we did have that squint tool that we used.

817
00:49:43,781 --> 00:49:47,523
So we do use those terms just in our day-to-day work.

818
00:49:49,044 --> 00:49:50,485
And how we've carried those forward

819
00:49:50,805 --> 00:49:52,946
into new design techniques, maybe I'll

820
00:49:52,966 --> 00:49:53,847
be able to talk about next year.

821
00:49:59,789 --> 00:50:14,840
You touched on the fact that in Black Ops, he said Favela in the single player was one of the most popular maps, and in multiplayer it was the least popular, or one of the least popular. Do you have some insight on why that might be?

822
00:50:18,594 --> 00:50:22,937
I mean that was the whole point, like I can't say definitively, I don't have their analytics,

823
00:50:23,597 --> 00:50:28,761
but I would guess that it was so overwhelming that it was much more difficult to play, that

824
00:50:29,121 --> 00:50:32,023
there was enemies coming from everywhere, you couldn't pick them out, you didn't know

825
00:50:32,103 --> 00:50:35,646
which paths you should take, there was multiple options, it was just like every single bit

826
00:50:35,706 --> 00:50:42,851
of it was visually, orally, mentally stimulating, overstimulating, and I think a lot of people

827
00:50:42,891 --> 00:50:43,372
just gave up.

828
00:50:43,512 --> 00:50:45,013
and out of sheer confusion.

829
00:50:45,473 --> 00:50:46,274
That would be my guess.

830
00:50:46,954 --> 00:50:49,897
And based on the guys that I've talked to from that team,

831
00:50:51,318 --> 00:50:53,479
they kind of indicated that that was the case.

832
00:50:53,499 --> 00:51:00,345
Awesome.

833
00:51:01,005 --> 00:51:02,486
All right, thank you guys for your time and attention.

834
00:51:02,526 --> 00:51:02,947
Appreciate it.

